SIMPLE: redress
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Redress
<hw>Re*dress"</hw> <pr>(r⟦emac⟧*dr⟦ecr⟧s")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<ety>[Pref. <ets>re-</ets> + <ets>dress</ets>.]</ety> <def>To dress
again.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Redress</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Redress
<hw>Re*dress"</hw> <pr>(r⟦esl⟧*dr⟦ecr⟧s")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<ety>[F. <ets>redresser</ets> to straighten; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- +
<ets>dresser</ets> to raise, arrange. See <er>Dress.</er>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To put in order again; to set right; to emend; to
revise.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The common profit could she <qex>redress</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In yonder spring of roses intermixed⟦br⟧
With myrtle, find what to <qex>redress</qex> till noon.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your wish that I should <qex>redress</qex> a certain paper which
you had prepared.</q> <rj><qau>A. Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To set right, as a wrong; to repair, as an injury;
to make amends for; to remedy; to relieve from.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those wrongs, those bitter injuries, . . . ⟦br⟧
I doubt not but with honor to <qex>redress</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make amends or compensation to; to relieve of
anything unjust or oppressive; to bestow relief upon.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧'T is
thine, O king! the afflicted to <xex>redress</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Will Gaul or Muscovite <qex>redress ye</qex>?</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Redress</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Redress
<hw>Re*dress"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
redressing; a making right; reformation; correction; amendment.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Reformation of evil laws is commendable, but for us the more
necessary is a speedy <qex>redress</qex> of ourselves.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A setting right, as of wrong, injury, or opression;
<as>as, the <ex>redress</ex> of grievances</as>; hence, relief; remedy;
reparation; indemnification.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A few may complain without reason; but there is occasion for
<qex>redress</qex> when the cry is universal.</q>
<rj><qau>Davenant.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, gives relief; a
redresser.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fair majesty, the refuge and <qex>redress</qex>⟦br⟧
Of those whom fate pursues and wants oppress.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Redressal</ent>⟦br⟧
